(1, 1, '2012-05-21 11:45:00', '2012-05-21 11:45:00', 'Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!', 'Hello world!', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'hello-world', '', '', '2012-05-21 11:45:59', '2012-05-21 11:45:59', '', 0, 'http://lowpress.dev/?p=1', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(2, 1, '2012-05-21 11:45:00', '2012-05-21 11:45:00', 'This is an example page. It''s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I''m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin'' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickies to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href="http://lowpress.dev/wp-admin/">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!', 'Sample Page', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'sample-page', '', '', '2012-05-21 13:57:10', '2012-05-21 13:57:10', '', 0, 'http://lowpress.dev/?page_id=2', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3, 1, '2012-05-21 11:45:41', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 'Auto Draft', '', 'auto-draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2012-05-21 11:45:41', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://lowpress.dev/?p=3', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(4, 1, '2012-05-21 11:45:00', '2012-05-21 11:45:00', 'Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!', 'Hello world!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1-revision', '', '', '2012-05-21 11:45:00', '2012-05-21 11:45:00', '', 1, 'http://lowpress.dev/?p=4', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(5, 1, '2012-05-21 13:53:31', '2012-05-21 13:53:31', 'As developers we read about the ''best way'' to do things and understand the benefits of creating structured, tested, extendible code which will stand the test of time, but this doesn''t translate well to an environment where you''re building websites for non-technical clients who want full control over all of the content on their website and they want it yesterday.\r\n\r\nFor example, you get a new client and they want an ecommerce website with the ability to add promotional offers and restrict products to certain countries but also want content managed pages, a members section with restricted content, a wordpress blog, integration with their external marketing system, and a central place to manage everything. Oh. and they want to be able to easily hook up products to blog posts.\r\n\r\nWhere do you start? You don''t have time or budget to roll your own system. Magento does all of the ecommerce you need, but what about the the blog? You could run an instance of wordpress, but now you''ve got two different backend management systems but neither of them has a CMS powerful enough to drive the rest of the site. Drupal for the content management? That''s another backend system, and now you''ve got to try to integrate your customer logins, manage templates in 3 different locations and your client has three different systems to log into!\r\n\r\nThis isn''t ideal, is it? It''s incredibly messy and this isn''t what the client expected when they spent their marketing budget on you. Sure, we could try to simplify things and look for plugins within a single system which can meet your other requirements, but what problems will that cause in the long run, when a client wants a feature adding that isn''t supported on the plugin you''re using? Do you really want to be extending small-time ecommerce plugins written by lone developers on a procedural blogging system to implement complicated features that another system has had for years and has been bug tested by a large community of users? And what''s happened to our object oriented, dependency injected, unit tested code that we wanted?\r\n\r\nMaybe some people have the answer to this and I''ve been left in the dark? I would love to hear of the experiences of other people, so your responses would be hugely appreciated.\r\n\r\nIn this series I''m going to explore ways to resolve these problems to create a single flexible, fast, customer friendly system which allows you to as seamlessly as possible cover any specification thrown at you with as few compromises as possible.\r\n\r\nIt is worth noting here that this is series is not a tutorial - I do not have all the answers. It will be a ''journey of exploration'' with goals in mind and hopefully incremental steps to get us closer to our final goal.\r\n\r\nThis project will be open source and I would be thrilled if others get involved and contribute to this project, along with helping to blog ideas and progress as we go, so if you want to get involved please don''t hesitate to contact me and get involved.', 'It all starts with an idea', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'it-all-starts-with-an-idea', '', '', '2012-05-21 14:11:22', '2012-05-21 14:11:22', '', 0, 'http://lowpress.dev/?p=5', 0, 'post', '', 0),
